\begin_layout Standard
Textbook quantum mechanics asserts that the probability of a measurement
 can be computed from wave function of the system and the measuring observable
 
\emph on
exactly
\emph default
 while real measurements must be finite precision.
 Whether finite precision measurement in reality affect the idealized quantum
 concept, e.g., contextuality
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "PhysRevLett.83.3751,Mermin1999,BarrettKent2004"

\end_inset

, and the very foundation of quantum mechanics is still a problem.
 In this letter, we model the finite precision quantum measurement by quantum
 interval-valued probability measures (IVPMs) which provides not only a
 uniform framework to understand Gleason's theorem
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
cite{gleason1957,Redhead1987-REDINA,peres1995quantum}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and the Kochen-Specker theorem
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "kochenspecker1967,peres1995quantum,Redhead1987-REDINA,Griffiths2003"

\end_inset

 but also some examples which cannot be explained by the Born rule
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
