\begin_layout Standard
To formalize the idea of finite precision measurement, we next introduce
 the notion of quantum IVPM
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mu}$
\end_inset

.
 The latter replaces the infinitely precise interval 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1]$
\end_inset

 by a finite collection 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{I}$
\end_inset

 of intervals.
 Since the intervals 
\begin_inset Formula $\imposs=\left[0,0\right]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\necess=\left[1,1\right]$
\end_inset

 should be included in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{I}$
\end_inset

, and arithmetic operations on intervals satisfy 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "eq:interval-operations"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
 &  & [l_{1},r_{1}]+[l_{2},r_{2}]=[l_{1}+l_{2},r_{1}+r_{2}]\textrm{ and}\\
 &  & x[l,r]=\begin{cases}
[xl,xr] & \textrm{for }x\ge0\textrm{ ;}\\{}
[xr,xl] & \textrm{for }x\le0\textrm{ .}
\end{cases}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mu}:\events\rightarrow\mathscr{I}$
\end_inset

 is defined by the axioms: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mu}(\mathbb{0})=\left[0,0\right]$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mu}(\mathbb{1})=\left[1,1\right]$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mu}\left(\mathbb{1}-P\right)=\left[1,1\right]-\bar{\mu}\left(P\right)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For a set of mutually orthogonal projections 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ P_{i}\right\} _{i=1}^{N}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{i}P_{j}=\delta_{ij}P_{i}$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\bar{\mu}\left(\sum_{i=1}^{N}P_{i}\right)\subseteq\sum_{i=1}^{N}\bar{\mu}\left(P_{i}\right)\label{eq:QuantumInterval-valuedProbability-Inclusion}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
condition that provides only a bound and not an equivalence as in Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:QuantumProbability-Addition"

\end_inset

.
 For example, if we consider 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ P_{1},P_{2}\right\} =\left\{ P,\mathbb{1}-P\right\} $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mu}\left(P\right)=\left[l,r\right]$
\end_inset

, we have, when 
\begin_inset Formula $r-l=\ell>0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\bar{\mu}(\mathbb{1})=\left[1,1\right]\subsetneq\left[1-\ell,1+\ell\right]=\bar{\mu}\left(\mathbb{1}-P\right)+\bar{\mu}\left(P\right).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Formally, we can ask: what can we deduce about the state of a quantum system
 given a quantum IVPM, i.e., given observations done with finite resources.
 Since the probabilities are now intervals, it is intuitive to say a state
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 is consistent with 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mu}$
\end_inset

 on a projector
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{\rho}^{\mathrm{B}}\left(P\right)\in\bar{\mu}\left(P\right)$
\end_inset

, and denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho\in\coreBorn\left(\bar{\mu},\left\{ P\right\} \right)$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover, 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho\in\coreBorn\left(\bar{\mu},S\right)$
\end_inset

 means 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 is consistent with 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mu}$
\end_inset

 on every projector in 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since our measurement is fuzzy, generally there are more than one state
 consistent with a particular quantum IVPM.
 For example, consider three intervals 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[0,0\right]$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[1,1\right]$
\end_inset

 and 
\emph on

\begin_inset Formula $\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset


\emph default
, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[0,0\right]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[1,1\right]$
\end_inset

 are called 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
imposs
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
necess
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

as before, and 
\emph on

\begin_inset Formula $\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset


\emph default
 is called 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
unknown
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

because it provides no information.
 Then,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\bar{\mu}_{1}\left(P\right)=\begin{cases}
\necess & \text{, if }P=\mathbb{1}\text{ ;}\\
\imposs & \text{, if }P=\mathbb{0}\text{ ;}\\
\unknown & \text{, otherwise,}
\end{cases}\label{eq:no-information-IVPM}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

is a quantum IVPM.
 This measure represents the beliefs of an experimenter with no prior knowledge
 about the particular quantum system in question, and any state is consistent
 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mu}_{1}$
\end_inset

 on any projectors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Quantum and Classical IVPMs
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Quantum IVPMs become classical IVPMs
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "JamisonLodwick2004"

\end_inset

 when the space of events includes only mutually commuting sub-events, where
 
\family roman
\size normal

\begin_inset Formula $\events'\subseteq\events$
\end_inset

 is called a sub-event space if it satisfies the following conditions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\family roman
\size normal
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbb{0},\mathbb{1}\right\} \subseteq\events'$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For any projection
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $P\in\events'$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{1}-P\in\events'$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For a set of mutually orthogonal projections
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ P_{i}\right\} _{i=1}^{N}\subseteq\events'$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i=1}^{N}P_{i}\in\events'$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For example, 
\begin_inset Formula $\events_{0}=\left\{ \mathbb{0},\proj{0},\proj{1},\mathbb{1}\right\} $
\end_inset

 is a commuting sub-event space.
 Restricting 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mu}_{1}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\events_{0}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mu}_{1}|_{\events_{0}}$
\end_inset

, gives a classical IVPM
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mu}_{2}$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}\bar{\mu}_{2}(\mathbb{0}) & =\imposs & \bar{\mu}_{2}(\proj{0}) & =\unknown\\
\bar{\mu}_{2}(\mathbb{1}) & =\necess & \bar{\mu}_{2}(\proj{1}) & =\unknown
\end{aligned}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

If we identify the density matrices
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\proj{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\proj{1}$
\end_inset

 as the head and the tail of a coin, respectively, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mu}_{2}$
\end_inset

 represents experimenter know nothing about a coin before she tosses it,
 and two classical states
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\proj{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\proj{1}$
\end_inset

 are both consistent with 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mu}_{2}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\events_{0}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In general, although measurements done with limited resources and poor precision
 may not uniquely identify the true state of a classical system, when the
 system satisfies an extra-condition called convex, there is always at least
 one system that is consistent with the measurements.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{definition}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mu}$
\end_inset

 is called convex if for all commuting 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{0},P_{1}\in\events$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mu}\left(P_{0}\vee P_{1}\right)+\bar{\mu}\left(P_{0}P_{1}\right)\subseteq\bar{\mu}\left(P_{0}\right)+\bar{\mu}\left(P_{1}\right)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{0}\vee P_{1}=P_{0}+P_{1}-P_{0}P_{1}$
\end_inset


